1) What is a Servlet?
A Servlet is a Java class used to create dynamic web applications.
It runs on a web server (like Tomcat) and handles client requests and generates responses (usually HTML).
________________________________________
2) What are the main phases of the Servlet lifecycle?
The servlet lifecycle has 3 main phases:
1.	init() ‚Äì Called once when the servlet is created.
2.	service() ‚Äì Called for every request.
3.	destroy() ‚Äì Called once before servlet is removed.
________________________________________
3) What is the difference between GenericServlet and HttpServlet?
GenericServlet	HttpServlet
Protocol independent	HTTP specific
Overrides service()	Overrides doGet(), doPost()
Used rarely	Mostly used in web apps
üëâ In real projects, we mostly extend HttpServlet.
________________________________________
4) Difference between doGet() and doPost()
doGet()	doPost()
Data sent in URL	Data sent in body
Limited data size	No size limit
Less secure	More secure
Used for fetching data	Used for form submission
________________________________________
5) What is ServletConfig?
ServletConfig is used to get initialization parameters of a specific servlet.
Example:
<init-param>
   <param-name>username</param-name>
   <param-value>admin</param-value>
</init-param>
________________________________________
6) What is ServletContext?
ServletContext is used to share data between all servlets in an application.
Example:
getServletContext().setAttribute("name", "Ragu");
________________________________________
7) What is RequestDispatcher?
Used to forward request from one servlet to another resource.
RequestDispatcher rd = request.getRequestDispatcher("home.jsp");
rd.forward(request, response);
üëâ URL does NOT change.
________________________________________
8) What is sendRedirect()?
Redirects client to another resource.
response.sendRedirect("home.jsp");
üëâ URL changes.
________________________________________
9) What are different ways of session management?
1.	Cookies
2.	HttpSession
3.	URL Rewriting
4.	Hidden Fields
________________________________________
10) What is web.xml?
Deployment descriptor file used to configure:
‚Ä¢	Servlet mapping
‚Ä¢	Init parameters
‚Ä¢	Filters
‚Ä¢	Listeners
________________________________________
üü° INTERMEDIATE LEVEL (11‚Äì20)
________________________________________
11) What is HttpSession?
Used to maintain user session between multiple requests.
HttpSession session = request.getSession();
session.setAttribute("user", "Ragu");
________________________________________
12) What are Cookies?
Small pieces of data stored in the browser.
Cookie c = new Cookie("user", "Ragu");
response.addCookie(c);
________________________________________
13) What are Filters?
Filters are used to:
‚Ä¢	Validate login
‚Ä¢	Logging
‚Ä¢	Modify request/response
Example:
@WebFilter("/*")
________________________________________
14) What are Listeners?
Used to listen for events like:
‚Ä¢	Session creation
‚Ä¢	Session destruction
‚Ä¢	Context initialization
Example:
@WebListener
________________________________________
15) What is @WebServlet annotation?
Used instead of web.xml.
@WebServlet("/login")
________________________________________
16) Is Servlet thread-safe?
No ‚ùå
Servlets are not thread-safe because multiple threads access the same instance.
________________________________________
17) How do you make a servlet thread-safe?
1.	Avoid instance variables
2.	Use local variables
3.	Synchronization (not recommended)
________________________________________
18) What is MVC in Servlets?
MVC = Model View Controller
‚Ä¢	Servlet ‚Üí Controller
‚Ä¢	JSP ‚Üí View
‚Ä¢	Java Class ‚Üí Model
________________________________________
19) What happens if init() throws exception?
Servlet will not be loaded and server throws ServletException.
________________________________________
20) What is load-on-startup?
Used to load servlet at server startup.
<load-on-startup>1</load-on-startup>
________________________________________
üî¥ ADVANCED LEVEL (21‚Äì30)
________________________________________
21) What is the difference between forward() and sendRedirect()?
forward()	sendRedirect()
Server-side	Client-side
Same request	New request
Faster	Slower
________________________________________
22) Can we override service() method?
Yes.
But usually we override doGet() or doPost().
________________________________________
23) How does servlet handle multiple requests?
Container creates multiple threads for same servlet instance.
________________________________________
24) What is SingleThreadModel?
Old interface used to make servlet thread-safe.
Now deprecated ‚ùå
________________________________________
25) What is difference between getRequestDispatcher() and getNamedDispatcher()?
‚Ä¢	getRequestDispatcher() ‚Üí by path
‚Ä¢	getNamedDispatcher() ‚Üí by servlet name
________________________________________
26) How do you handle exception in servlet?
1.	Try-catch block
2.	web.xml error-page mapping
3.	Custom error page
________________________________________
27) What is URL rewriting?
Appending session ID in URL:
http://example.com/home;jsessionid=12345
Used when cookies are disabled.
________________________________________
28) What is asynchronous servlet?
Used for long-running tasks without blocking threads.
@WebServlet(asyncSupported = true)
________________________________________
29) What is difference between getWriter() and getOutputStream()?
getWriter()	getOutputStream()
Text data	Binary data
HTML	PDF, Image
________________________________________
30) How do you secure a servlet?
1.	Use HTTPS
2.	Configure security in web.xml
3.	Use filters for authentication
4.	Use Spring Security (advanced)

